Why does my phone say sos only

2025-06-20T22:16:38.764018Z assistant

When your phone says SOS only, it usually means its not connected to your carriers network, but it can still make emergency calls. Here are the most common causes and how to fix them:

1. No SIM or SIM Not Recognized

  • Fix:
    • Go to Settings > Cellular > SIM Applications or Cellular Plans.
    • Remove and reinsert the SIM card (if physical).
    • If using eSIM, ensure it's activated and assigned to a data plan.

2. No Signal or Out of Coverage Area

  • Fix:
    • Try going to a different location with better reception.
    • Toggle Airplane Mode ON and OFF.
    • Restart the phone.

3. Carrier Issues

  • Your carrier might be down or blocked your line (e.g., for non-payment or fraud protection).
  • Fix:
    • Contact your carrier (T-Mobile in your case).
    • Log into your T-Mobile account to check for suspensions or alerts.

4. Phone Is Locked to a Carrier

  • If the phone is carrier-locked (like T-Mobile) and you're trying to use another SIM or eSIM, it might show SOS only.
  • Fix:
    • Check under Settings > General > About to see if Carrier Lock says No SIM restrictions.
    • If its locked, youll need to request an unlock from T-Mobile.

5. Incorrect Network Settings

  • Fix:
    • Reset network settings:
      Settings > General > Transfer or Reset > Reset > Reset Network Settings.

6. eSIM Not Fully Activated

  • If you're trying to use a Google Fi or other temporary plan:
    • Make sure activation steps were fully completed on Wi-Fi.
    • Check for confirmation in the provider's app or website.

Want me to walk through steps based on your current phone setup? If you tell me:

  • What phone youre on
  • What carrier/SIM/eSIM setup you're using
  • What plan you're trying to activate
    Ill give you an exact fix.

Why wouldnt it work on WiFi tho

2025-06-20T22:18:31.980654Z assistant

Great question.

When you're seeing SOS only even though you're connected to Wi-Fi, that tells us something specific:

Here's the core idea:

Wi-Fi doesnt affect your ability to connect to the mobile network it just gives you internet access.

But unless youre using Wi-Fi Calling or a service like Google Voice, your phone still needs a valid SIM/eSIM and cellular signal to:

  • send/receive SMS
  • make/receive calls
  • connect to your carrier

So why wouldnt it work over Wi-Fi alone?

1. Wi-Fi Calling isn't enabled or supported

Even though you're on Wi-Fi, Wi-Fi Calling is not automatically active. It has to be:

  • Supported by your carrier
  • Enabled manually:
    Settings > Cellular > Wi-Fi Calling > Turn On

Without this, your phone tries to use the cellular network first and if it's unavailable, you get SOS only.

2. eSIM Activation Still Requires a Network Check

Even with Wi-Fi:

  • Most eSIM activations still require your phone to talk to the carrier's servers via cellular signal (especially for initial provisioning).
  • Some providers like Google Fi or T-Mobile do allow Wi-Fi-based activation, but it might hang if:
    • Theres an account issue (not paid, not provisioned)
    • You didnt finish the QR code or app setup steps
    • The eSIM profile didn't install properly

3. Carrier Lock or Block
